<subSubSection id="334D9B552575DB1E2D23D5BEB2739A6C" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9C55C8CC9B012E067BF8BF0E0AB40D98" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="04E216474D920C649EC841A341C0277C" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Haiti, Dominican Republic, Puerto Rico, and U.S. Virgin Islands.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D998ADDA08FE047998ECE8A628A1CAF9" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="D0836B9429A1B109335B81BE20AC9EF4" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB6CD071DDB2CADC0E5BA6570DC1FD1F" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Forests from sea level to 1000 m, primarily on calcareous soils, but in Puerto Rico also on serpentine-derived soils.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F842E3EA6F0B4D7C20C0CCA29059E2D8" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="E48D8B3110BD7657C6BF8DFB34D2C2FC" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A51DF45F11DB6E91F2B81BA1CF99748C" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Flowering primarily January to April, rarely as early as November. Fruiting February to August.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0769731C4556612F4A744DE5D00B3F69" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="BE4A938EE4D29868FBBD553FEE3835A3" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="801037A332D1FE3DDB56D7ED39ED9D12" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Least concern. 
<taxonomicName id="B22EF0787AC89333F0A0A1688A083284" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Drypetes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Geraniales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis id="980F49E3A69D05AFF1A232103B9C2A34" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Drypetes alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
var. 
<emphasis id="4319321B0D33F4312EF26117F1DCC9D0" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">alba</emphasis>
is widespread and likely secure in the Dominican Republic, Puerto Rico, and U.S. Virgin Islands. It may be vulnerable or endangered in Haiti due to extensive deforestation there; I have seen no specimens from Haiti collected later than 1929.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
